<HTML>
<TITLE>ILLEGITIMACY'S DISASTROUS EFFECTS</TITLE>
<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<P>
<H2>ILLEGITIMACY'S DISASTROUS EFFECTS</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
<LI>  Out of wedlock pregnancy is a near certain predictor of poverty.
 The one-parent family is six times more likely to be poor than
the two-parent family.
<P>
 
<LI>  Women who bear illegitimate children (especially before finishing
high school) are far more likely to rely on government to support
their children and to spend more years on welfare once enrolled.
<P>
<LI>  Children born outside of marriage are three times more likely
to depend on welfare themselves when they reach adulthood.
<P>
<LI>  Illegitimacy feeds itself.  Young white women who grow up without
a father in the home are more than twice as likely to bear children
out of wedlock.  And boys living in a single-parent family are
twice as likely to father a child out of wedlock as boys from
intact homes.
<P>
<LI>  More than 70% of all juveniles in state reform institutions
come from fatherless homes.  The relationship between crime and
one-parent families is so powerful that controlling for family
structure erases the relationship between crime and race or poverty.
<P>
<LI>  The likelihood that a young male will engage in criminal activities
doubles if he is raised without a father and triples if he lives
in a neighborhood with a high concentration of single-parent families.
<P>
<LI>  The greater the incidence of single-parent families in a neighborhood,
the higher the incidence of violent crime and burglary.
<P>
<LI>  Teenage single-parent mothering is the single greatest contributor
to low birth weight babies.  Studies show that the high rate of
out-of-wedlock births to young mothers is the primary explanation
for America's low international standing on measures of infant
mortality.
<P>
<LI>  Children born out of wedlock are much more likely to experience
abuse or neglect.
<P>
<LI>  Children born out of wedlock are more likely to experience
impaired physical development and low cognitive/verbal development.
 Among children aged 3-5 in one study, those with teen mothers
were twice as likely to have few children's books in the home.
<P>
<LI>  Children from single-parent families are two to three times
more likely to have emotional or behavioral problems than children
from intact families.  They also exhibit weaker peer adjustment
and a weaker sense of right and wrong.
<P>
<LI>  Children from fatherless homes have lower educational aspirations
and a low level of educational achievement.  Studies also show
that illegitimacy reduces job performance, professional attainment,
individual income, and the overall health of the economy.

<p>

<center>
<b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/infocus/">Other Infocus</a>] 
