<html>
<title>CAREERS: A MISSED OPPORTUNITY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<p>
<h2>CAREERS:<br>
A MISSED OPPORTUNITY</h2></center>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>
On Sept. 19, 1995, the U.S. House of Representatives voted in
favor of the CAREERS Act (H.R. 2332), a bill which would consolidate
about 100 job training programs into three.  They call it a victory
because they've streamlined programs and saved money.  We call
it a failure to uproot key elements of the Goals 2000 agenda.
<p>
While sponsors of the bill accepted some of the changes suggested
by pro-family groups, they were unwilling to strike references
to the National Skill Standards Board (NSSB) and a requirement
that state skill standards be referenced to the national skill
standards to be developed by that board.  NSSB was a creation
of the National Skill Standards Act of 1994, a part of the same
public law as Goals 2000 (Pub. Law 103-227), and in keeping with
its philosophy.  NSSB would fund, oversee, and endorse the creation
of a national system of skill standards, certificates, and assessments;
it is to occupational skills what the National Education Goals
Panel is to academics.  Yet some conservative members of Congress
failed to see the flaws in such a system.
<p>
One small victory was the addition of language to prohibit any
requirement that a student meet federally funded or endorsed skill
standards or obtain a federally funded or endorsed skill certificate.
 Because this provision has the potential to undermine significantly
the influence of the National Skill Standards Board, this provision
could be a prime target as the bill goes to conference.
<p>
CAREERS will now go to a House-Senate Conference Committee to
work out differences between versions passed in the two houses.
 Unfortunately,  Sen. Nancy Kassebaum's (R-Kan.) job training
bill (S. 143) embraces the philosophy advanced in the liberal
School-to-Work Act of 1994 even more than CAREERS does.  This
may threaten even the minor improvements gained in the House bill.
<p>
The 104th Congress has unfinished business in education.   No
adequate proposal to repeal Goals 2000 has yet been advanced.
 Rep. Duke Cunningham (R-Calif.) claims his &quot;Education Reform
Consolidation Grant&quot;  would repeal Goals 2000,  but it does
so only in name.   Its core elements remain intact:  the National
Education Goals Panel, the National Education Goals, and bullying
the states on how to reform.  Does it make sense for a &quot;reformist&quot;
Congress to pass on the meddlesome, bureaucratic, centralizing
legacy of Goals 2000 and School-to-Work, rather than put an end
to it?
<p>
-- 9/21/95

<p>

