<HTML>
<TITLE>FAMILIES NEED TAX FREEDOM</TITLE>
<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<P>
<H2>FAMILIES NEED TAX FREEDOM<BR>
</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
<CENTER>
<I>by</I>
<P>
<I> William R. Mattox, Jr.</I></CENTER>
<P>
Now that May
6 has finally arrived, families across America can breathe a sigh
of relief.  For May 6 is Tax Freedom Day, the day when Americans
cease working to support The Tax Man and start working to support
their families.
<P>
That's right, when you calculate how many days
one would have to work to pay off all the taxes owed by the average
taxpayer, the Tax Foundation in Washington reports that one would
not be free to keep their own earnings until May 6.
<P>
 But if the
new Republican House of Representatives has its way, tax freedom
will come sooner in the future.
<P>
The House recently passed a major
income tax cut that was hailed as the &quot;crown jewel&quot;
of its Contract with America.  The tax cut bill had a number of
 important pro-family features -- including a provision to make
it easier to claim home office deductions and a provision to write
off expenses associated with adopting a child.  But no provision
in the bill is as important as the bill's centerpiece:  a new
$500 children's tax credit for taxpaying parents.
<P>
The $500 children's
tax credit is designed to address the steady erosion in per-child
tax benefits that has occurred over the last four decades.  This
erosion in per-child benefits is part of the reason the average
family today sends Uncle Sam nearly a quarter of every dollar
earned, whereas the average family in 1950 sent only two-cents
of every dollar earned to the federal government.  And it is the
chief reason several national commissions -- including the 1986
White House Working Group on the Family and the 1991 National
Commission on Children -- made pro-family tax relief their top
policy recommendation.
<P>
  Unfortunately, the fate of the House GOP's
tax cut bill is very uncertain in the Senate.  Several key Republican
Senators -- most especially, Finance Committee Chairman Robert
Packwood (R-OR) -- have publicly raised doubts about tax cuts
in general, and the per-child tax credit in particular.  Others,
like Senators Dan Coats (R-IN) and Rod Grams (R-MN), have pledged
to take a $500 tax credit proposal to the Senate floor if Packwood
blocks committee passage of a bill patterned after the House GOP
Contract.
<P>
The fact that parents need tax relief can be seen not
just in the economic statistics showing a dramatic rise in the
tax burden facing Americans, but also in the
cultural statistics William Bennett publishes showing a dramatic
decline in the various indices of family well-being.  
<P>
To be sure,
pro-family tax relief cannot single-handedly solve these problems.
 Pro-family tax relief cannot cause husbands to love their wives
or children to respect their parents.  It cannot clean up filthy
TV or remove child predators from neighborhood streets.  It cannot
improve the quality of America's schools.
<P>
In short, pro-family
tax relief cannot, by itself, magically solve the various social
problems facing America's families, neighborhoods, and communities.
<P>
But
pro-family tax-relief will make it easier for families to thrive
by reducing economic stress on financially-strapped parents. 
It will make it easier for time-starved parents to monitor their
children's TV viewing habits and after-school play activities
and educational studies.
<P>
In essence, pro-family tax relief will
empower parents to address many family needs that only they can
meet.  As such, pro-family tax relief is a useful complement to
the cuts in wasteful government and social programs. 
<P>
 Hopefully,
the full Senate will soon adopt a $500 tax credit for children.
 Such a credit is needed, if Tax Freedom Day is to come any sooner
in the years ahead.
<P>
<CENTER> ***</CENTER>
<P><I>William R. Mattox, Jr. is the Vice President
for Policy of the Family Research Council, a Washington, DC-based
research and advocacy organization.</I>

<p>

