<html>
<title>THE FIRST LADY'S PARTICIPATION IN BEIJING CONFERENCE</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>THE FIRST LADY'S PARTICIPATION IN<br>
BEIJING CONFERENCE<br>
SENDS THE WRONG MESSAGE</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Gracie S. Hsu</i></center>
<p>
Within hours of Harry Wu's safe return to the United States, the
Clinton Administration announced First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's
intention to go to Beijing for the United Nations Fourth World
Conference on Women.  After weeks of debate and uncertainty regarding
her participation, the Clintons felt Harry Wu's release paved
the way for the First Lady to attend without further barriers.
 But the Clintons are mistaken:  there remain several significant
reasons why Mrs. Clinton should not attend this conference.
<P>
First, Harry Wu was shamelessly used by the Chinese government
as a bargaining chip.  Unfortunately, the Clinton Administration
bought into China's tactic 100 percent.  By &quot;rewarding&quot;
China for its &quot;good&quot; behavior of expelling human rights
activist Harry Wu after convicting him of &quot;crimes,&quot;
the United States demonstrates that despotic regimes like China
should be free to take and use political prisoners as leverage
to strongarm the U.S. into accommodating their wishes.  The U.S.
position in this sends a clear message to China and to other nations
that the U.S. is willing to abide by the perverse rules of extortion.
<P>
Secondly, the Clinton Administration wrongly assumes that Harry
Wu's return to the United States clears the way for the First
Lady to attend the conference by exonerating China.  It does not.
 Indeed, during his first speech to the public after returning
from China, Mr. Wu strongly urged Mrs. Clinton to forgo her participation
in the Beijing conference because of China's blatant disregard
for human rights.  Mr. Wu said that the First Lady's attendance
would send China &quot;a signal, a kind of approval&quot; that
the United States is willing to tolerate, even condone, such crimes
against humanity.
<P>
And human rights abuses in China abound.  From forced sterilization
and coercive abortion policies, to female infanticide, to slave
labor (which Harry Wu placed himself at considerable risk to document),
to the killing of prisoners to harvest their organs for transplant
procedures, to cannibalizing aborted fetuses, to religious persecution,
to the quashing of human rights at all levels by the ruthless
communist Chinese government, the Chinese people inhumanely suffer
at the hands of their own government.  Indeed, the only difference
between the Tiananmen Square massacre and the ghastly human 
rights abuses that occur every day in China is that Tiananmen
was witnessed by the public.
<P>
Perhaps because the Tiananmen massacre has been permanently etched
into America's consciousness, the public outcry against Mrs. Clinton's
attendance in Beijing has been strong and swift.  As a result,
the Clinton Administration has been prompted to defend Mrs. Clinton's
attendance by contending that she will be able to:  (1) speak
out against China's human rights violations and (2) advance women's
rights.  However, it is doubtful that the First Lady will be able
to accomplish either of these objectives by participating in this
conference.
<P>
First, while we earnestly hope that Mrs. Clinton will highlight
China's human rights abuses, it is also noteworthy that Geraldine
Ferraro, a Clinton Administration-appointed delegate to the United
Nations conference, requested that the Beijing document's condemnation
of  &quot;trafficking in human organs and tissue&quot; -- a barbaric
practice largely associated with China -- remain bracketed for
removal.  In other words, Ms. Ferraro blocked this language from
being officially incorporated into the document.  That an official
U.S. delegate was unwilling to have the conference document even
<I>mention</I> one of China's most egregious human rights violations
during an unpublicized consultatory meeting makes it that much
more improbable that the First Lady would dare to condemn China's
abuses in the highly publicized setting of Beijing. 
<P>
Furthermore, a great chasm exists between doing something about
human rights abuses and merely talking about them.  A strong stand
by the Clinton Administration to withhold the First Lady's attendance
on the grounds that China abuses women would have shown words
backed by action.  But now the Administration has only words.
 And if the adage is true that actions speak louder than words,
then Mrs. Clinton's words will have little impact since she is
in Beijing delivering them.  Worst of all, her distinguished presence
at the conference confers on China the international spotlight
it desires and the legitimacy it seeks.
<P>
Finally, if the First Lady intends to uphold women's rights, then
she should not be attending the Beijing conference at all.  The
Beijing document's Platform for Action does not represent the
large majority of American women (or the women of any other country,
for that matter) on the central issues of motherhood and the family.
 Rather, it promotes a radical feminist agenda which undermines
the natural family unit and erodes the foundations of marriage
and family life, while upholding abortion and the dissemination
of contraceptives to minors as positive alternatives.
<P>
From the beginning of Harry Wu's imprisonment, the Clinton Administration
has been adamant in its resolve to send a  U.S. delegation to
the Beijing conference.  The U.S. refused to take a firm stand
then.  But with Wu's release, it would have been only a small
price to pay for the U.S. to finally take a stand -- albeit symbolic
-- by having Mrs. Clinton refuse to attend the conference.  That
the Clinton Administration failed to do even that is disturbing.
<P>
-- 8/31/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<I>Gracie S. Hsu is a policy analyst at the Family Research Council,
a Washington D.C.-based research and advocacy organization.</I>

