<html>
<title>NEW WELFARE POLL SHOWS STRONG SUPPORT FOR COMBATTING 
ILLEGITIMACY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>NEW WELFARE POLL SHOWS<br>
STRONG SUPPORT FOR<br>
COMBATTING ILLEGITIMACY</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Gary L. Bauer</i></center>
<p>
Opposition runs strong and deep to &quot;increasing a welfare
mother's monthly welfare check if she has another child out of
wedlock,&quot; according to a new national poll commissioned by
the Family Research Council.
<p>
Two-thirds (66 percent) of the 1,000 Americans surveyed said they
&quot;strongly&quot; oppose such increases.  Another 18 percent
said they &quot;somewhat&quot; oppose welfare benefit increases
for illegitimacy.  Only 13 percent said these increases were justified.
<p>
These findings should allay any doubts Congressional Republicans
may have about whether the public supports their &quot;family
cap&quot; proposal to cease welfare benefit increases when women
bear additional children out of wedlock.  The &quot;family cap&quot;
is a central feature of the welfare reform legislation House and
Senate GOP leaders will be sending soon to the President.
<p>
Interestingly, support for the family cap among rank-and-file
pro-lifers is at least as strong as support from other Americans.
 Among those who &quot;strongly&quot; favor prohibitions against
abortion, 70 percent &quot;strongly&quot; support the family cap,
and another 16 percent &quot;somewhat&quot; support such an approach.
 (Some pro-life leaders have expressed concern that the &quot;family
cap&quot; might increase abortions, while others have argued that
curbing out-of-wedlock pregnancy will lower the number of abortions
long term since most abortions are to unmarried women.)
<p>
The FRC poll also found that Americans are more hopeful about
efforts to combat illegitimacy than about &quot;workfare&quot;
strategies.
<p>
By a margin of roughly two-to-one (64 percent to 33 percent),
Americans say &quot;getting young people to delay having children
until they are able to support themselves and a family&quot; is a more 
attainable goal than &quot;getting single mothers with few job skills into 
jobs that will pay them enough to support themselves and their children.&quot;
<p>
This does not mean Americans oppose workfare.  In fact, fully
90 percent say welfare recipients should have to work for their
benefits.
<p>
But the poll results do suggest that Americans expect policymakers
to give at least as much attention to a preventative, anti-illegitimacy
strategy as they do to a remedial, workfare strategy.
<p>
And should there not be enough &quot;workfare&quot; jobs to go
around, most Americans believe welfare mothers of preschool children
should be permitted to go to the back of the line.
<p>
Eighty-two percent say preschool moms should be the &quot;last&quot;
group required to work for benefits.  Most say &quot;mothers of
school-aged children&quot; and (especially) &quot;fathers of dependent
children&quot; should have to meet work requirements first.
<p>
These findings suggest that significant increases in day care
spending are not needed to complement &quot;workfare&quot; requirements,
since neither House would require states to provide jobs for all
welfare recipients.
<p>
The FRC poll was conducted in mid-October by Voter/Consumer Research,
a research firm based in Bethesda, Maryland.  The poll surveyed
1,000 randomly-selected Americans.  It has a margin for error
of plus or minus three percent.
<p>
-- 11/1/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Gary L. Bauer is president of the Family Research Council in
Washington, D.C.</i>

