<html>
<title>ARE TEXAS' ILLEGITIMACY NUMBERS LEGITIMATE?</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<p>
<h2>ARE TEXAS' ILLEGITIMACY NUMBERS LEGITIMATE?</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>William R. Mattox, Jr.</i></center>
<p>
As the welfare reform debate turns increasingly to the states,
a number of folks interested in finding effective ways to combat
illegitimacy have been intrigued by something going on deep in
the heart of Texas.  Apparently, when it comes to having babies,
women seldom go it alone in the Lone Star State.
<p>
Whereas nearly one in three babies (31 percent) nationally is
born to a single mother, the most recent data available from the
National Center for Health Statistics show that roughly one in
six Texas tots (17 percent) is born out of wedlock.  Only Utah
(15 percent) has a lower ratio of non-marital to marital births.
<p>
What is remarkable -- and somewhat curious -- about the Lone Star
State's relatively low illegitimacy ratio is that it runs counter
to nearly every major national trend.  Generally, illegitimacy
tends to be higher in states with populations that are disproportionately
young, poor, or black -- all of which are true of Texas.
<p>
Indeed, New Mexico, Louisiana, Mississippi, and the District of
Columbia have the nation's highest illegitimacy ratios, while
Idaho, New Hampshire, and North Dakota follow Utah and Texas in
the Top Five for low illegitimacy.
<p>
So what explains the Lone Star State's apparent success?  Why
is Texas the only state along America's southern border that has
an illegitimacy ratio below the national average?
<p>
No one knows for sure.  But those hoping that Texas has found
some magic bullet for dramatically reducing our nation's serious
illegitimacy problem are apt to be disappointed.
<p>
Here's why:  NCHS shows that while Texas has a non-marital birth
rate well below the national average, it also has a teen pregnancy
rate well above the national average.  In fact, 45 states have a lower teen
pregnancy rate than Texas.  Thus, the Lone Star State's low illegitimacy
ratio apparently is not due to the success of its teen pregnancy
prevention programs.  Nor is it apparently attributable to rampant
abortion, since the abortion rate in Texas is below the national
average.
<p>
How, then, does one explain the fact that the Lone Star State
simultaneously has one of the highest teen pregnancy rates in
the country and one of the lowest illegitimacy ratios?  Here are
three possible explanations:
<p>
<b>1. The Shotgun Marriage Theory</b>. It used to be that girls
who got pregnant out of wedlock would, with the aid of their enraged
fathers, convince their boyfriends to marry them prior to the
arrival of their child.  Thus, many out-of-wedlock pregnancies
ended up being in-wedlock births.
<p>
In recent years, of course, shotgun marriages have fallen out
of fashion.  And while NCHS does not have data comparing the age
of first marriage for Texas women to that of women from other
states, there is little reason to believe shotgun marriages are
making a major comeback in Texas -- even though the Lone Star
State does have a disproportionate number of shotgun owners.
<p>
<b>2. The Chevy Suburban Theory</b>.  Not only does Texas have
more shotgun owners than other states, but it also has more of
those gas-guzzling, road-hogging Chevy Suburbans that some like
to call &quot;Texas Station Wagons.&quot;  Why is this important?
 Because nine-passenger Chevy Suburbans are the ultimate Big Family
Car for married couples who have lots of children -- and when
marrieds have lots of children, the ratio of non-marital to marital
births is lowered.
<p>
Indeed, the reason Utah has the lowest illegitimacy ratio in the
country is not just because its highly-Mormon unmarried population
is less likely to engage in the kind of hanky-panky that leads
to early pregnancy.  It is also because its highly-Mormon married
population is very reproductive by today's standards.
<p>
The most recent stats from the Census Bureau show that Texas women
are bearing children at a rate well below that of Utah women.
 But these stats are several years old, so it is at least conceivable
that Texas couples have recently started reproducing like rabbits
to fill their Suburbans.  It is more likely, of course, that many
Texas families are driving those gas-guzzling Suburbans (instead
of more practical seven-passenger minivans) because a good Texan
would never own a &quot;mini&quot; anything.
<p>
<b>3. The Texans Tell Tall Tales Theory</b>.  Another possibility
is that Texas' illegitimacy numbers are illegitimate -- that the
Lone Star State's data reflect that time-tested Texas tendency
to tell tall tales.  Sad to say, one need not hail from the &quot;Show
Me State&quot; (Missouri) to be skeptical about the veracity of
Texas' numbers.  The reason?  NCHS reports that Texas is one of
six states that does not require a mother's marital status to
be identified on her child's birth certificate.
<p>
Thus, NCHS says the illegitimacy numbers Texas reports to NCHS
are &quot;inferred.&quot;  This is a fancy way of saying the numbers
are made up.  They are educated guesses, to be sure.  By educated
people no doubt.  But they are, in the end, still guesses.
<p>
Curiously, Texas leaped from 23rd in the nation in low teen illegitimacy
in 1989 to 9th nationally in 1990 -- the very year Texas made
it easier for births to be &quot;inferred&quot; as marital.  Thus,
Texas' dramatic &quot;improvement&quot; in illegitimacy in recent
years is almost surely due to the fact that Texas officials have
been &quot;inferring&quot; lots of births incorrectly.
<p>
To their credit, some straight-shooters at the Texas Bureau of
Vital Statistics recently changed the procedure for reporting
birth information so that a mother's marital status must be identified.
 The effects of this change won't be reported by NCHS until next
spring, but preliminary indications are that Texas' illegitimacy
ratio will climb to about 29 percent.
<p>
That is significantly higher than the Lone Star State's current
ratio, but it is still lower than the national average -- and
lower than all of its neighbors.
<p>
Which is to say Texas probably doesn't have a magic bullet in
its fight against illegitimacy, but it does have an illegitimacy
ratio just good enough to give Texans reason to do what Texans
do best: boast.
<p>
-- 11/9/95
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>William R. Mattox, Jr. is the vice president for policy at
the Family Research Council in Washington, D.C.  Lynne Edwards
of his staff provided valuable research assistance for this article</i>.

<p>

