<html>
<title>WATCHING IS NOT OKAY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>WATCHING IS NOT OKAY</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Kristi Hamrick</i></center>
<p>
What happened to Dr. Kevorkian as he worked in steel rooms cutting
into the last remains of someone's family? What happened to the
pathologist whose job it was to determine the way death came --
rather than to be the cause of that death?
<p>
What kind of thoughts entered his mind as he saw the signature
of death? Did he wish he could have been there? 
<p>
And then later, this scavenger of death, this man whose entire
living depended on the deaths of others, later his thoughts turned,
where?  To, &quot;I can be there&quot; or &quot;I can be the cause&quot;?
<p>
Recently Dr. Kevorkian was involved in another woman's death,
but this time, she wasn't so sick.  Physicians seemed to have
halted the decline toward death. Until Dr. Kevorkian.
<p>
And so we find in this drama that the reality was that the true
state of this woman's health was her mental health. And she was
abandoned to a voyeuristic death, Dr. Kevorkian having helped
her decide that her life wasn't worth living.
<p>
Or was it?
<p>
No one seems to remember that the first duty to one's depressed
friend -- to a fellow human being -- is not to speed them to death,
but to cheer them up and help them find the strength to go on.
We are inspired by the lovely wife of Christopher Reeve who helps
him see all that remains in life for him to accomplish.
<p>
But today they seem rare, for we live in a culture that glamorizes
death.
<p>
Recently my husband and I drove by a prominent theater in our
nation's capitol, and on the marquee every movie hawked a vision
of death. <I>Copy Cat</I> and the thrill of serial killing; <I>Devil
in a Blue Dress</I> and the fun of blackmail and betrayal, <I>Dead
Presidents</I> and the joy of a horrific war experience followed
by unemployment; <I>7</I> and the beauty of twisted 
justice; even a <I>Vampire in Brooklyn</I> and the spice of the
&quot;undead&quot; and their appetites.
<p>
But for those of us weaned on shootings and our &quot;right&quot;
to bad taste, no mere knowledge of death will do any longer for
some.
<p>
We can't know -- in Alfred Hitchcock fashion -- that someone in
the next room just left this mortal coil. Now we must see it,
slow motion, full color, <I>Pulp Fiction</I> frame by frame, until
we're so hardened to the sight of human suffering, that the nausea
rape, torture, murder and old fashioned fear just don't do much
for us anymore.
<p>
But blood isn't a big screen phenomena. If the money is not in
the budget for movies, there is always television.
<p>
One recent Friday night, free speech and hardened sensibilities
served up battery and slow death in prison on the <I>X-files</I>;
murderous people killing enemies by slow death by maggots on <I>American
Gothic</I>, and various forms of shootings, stabbings and stalkings
-- and that is without all those really seamy &quot;true-to-life&quot;
cop dramas where we not only get to see brain-like matter splatter,
we are exposed to portly policemen in the shower, making washing
decisions on a national screen despite what modesty and good taste
would indicate.
<p>
Having been a reporter who covered the court and police beats,
I can say first hand that  what is missing from these true to
life dramas is real life. Police are usually people working hard,
thinking of their kids, trying to find out what really happened
at the scene of a tragedy. They're not soap operas in blues. They
live out the unglamorous reality of hard work and dignified people.
<p>
So where does this leave America? Where does this lead the world?
Into the valley of the shadow of death, into the imagined worlds
of men like Dr. Kevorkian, who seems to believe that just because
he can invent a machine that kills he should be allowed to ...
and allowed to watch.
<p>
Ironically, when Dr. Kevorkian kills, the media responds by putting
on &quot;reasoned&quot; discussions of euthanasia, asking bubble-headed
bleach blonde questions about the &quot;right to die&quot; rather
than seeing that there is little difference between an elderly
man with a death machine, and kids killing kids with baseball
bats &quot;to watch.&quot;
<p>
News stories show us pictures of &quot;real life&quot; dramas
of children killing children to &quot;see what it was like&quot;
or to see a real murder. Children throwing tiny victims from high-rise
apartments. Children raping, stabbing and shooting. Life is worth
less than tennis shoes or jackets, and people have less worth
than laboratory rats.
<p>
Groups like People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals advocate
using coma patients and those classed as brain dead for medical
experiments rather than the kinds of creatures that civilizations
have historically understood to be of less worth than children.
And in a survey I heard about, some people don't seem to understand
that if a child and a dog were drowning, the child should be the
first saved.
<p>
Out of what hole did Dr. Kevorkian crawl? Where did his passion
for death come from? In part, one wonders, from the notion that accidental 
life isn't worth the DNA it haphazardly &quot;evolved&quot; on.
<p>
From the deliberate rejection of founding ideals like the holding
of truths to be self evident, that all people are created equal
&quot;and they are endowed by their creator with certain inalienable
rights, among these are life ...&quot;
<p>
Human life ... each one unique, valuable, irreplaceable. Each
person with something to offer. And it does not have to be the
same things ... nor even the same abilities to walk or think or
paint.
<p>
A society that loses the sanctity of life has nothing left to
share but death. If there are no reliable standards of right and
wrong, then there is no reason to persevere or overcome -- if
you don't want to. No reason for people to reach out to you in
your darkest moment if they don't feel like it.  If we have no
common dignity then we share, at least, a common end. And so our
culture seems to revel in death, both by  murderous flashing images
on a screen and the real live voyeurism of thugs and Dr. Kevorkian.
<p>
Somewhere along the line, Dr. Kevorkian seems to have decided
that he wanted to watch. In a civil society, the answer to that
is, &quot;No,&quot; and  &quot;Get some help.&quot;
<p>
Until we determine to embrace human life as the sacred and valuable
thing that it is, unique in all the world, and determine that
we will work together to enrich the human experience in practical
and real ways, we will have nothing in common but the fear and
fascination we have with the only thing we know for sure  -- the
fact that we will all die.
<p>
But there is more to life than death ... at least, there should
be.
<p>
-- 12/1/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Kristi Hamrick is director of communications at the Family
Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and advocacy
organization.</i>

<p>

