<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Chapter 3: Regulation: Additional Information - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 3 - Additional Information</h3>
<center>
<b>Return to <A HREF="chpt3.html">Chapter 3</a> | <a href="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</a></b></center> 
<P>


<center><b>THE TOP FIVE REGULATORY RECOMMENDATIONS FROM THE 1995 WHITE HOUSE CONFERENCE ON SMALL BUSINESS</b></center><ul>
<p><li><b>Congress should amend the Regulatory Flexibility Act,</b> making it applicable to all federal agencies, including the Internal Revenue Service and the Department of Defense, to include cost-benefit analysis; grant judicial review of regulations; require small business representation; and require the use of negotiated rulemaking with small business representation.
<p><li><b>Congress should reform the Comprehensive Environmental Response,</b> Compensation and Liability Act (CERCLA) to apply prospectively as well as retrospectively to clean up sites. This includes eliminating retroactive and strict liability prior to January 1, 1987; and requiring sound science and realistic risk assessments to assess health and environmental hazards.
<p><li><b>Congress shall mandate a complete review of current laws and regulations relating to public health and safety,</b> such as the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, the Clean Water Act, the Clean Air Act, the Endangered Species Act, and the National Environmental Policy Act.
<p><li><b>Congress and the President should propose and enact legislation that reforms civil justice and product liability legislation</b> that include: 1) returning to a fault-based standard of liability; 2) eliminating joint and several liability; 3) limiting non-economic damages to three times the economic damages or $250,000 which ever is greater; and 4) providing for periodic, instead of lump sum payments for future medical or lost income.
<p><li><b>Congress shall enact legislation and appropriate enforcement</b> that includes: 1) requiring that all agencies provide a cooperative/consulting regulatory environment; 2) requiring that fines take into consideration the severity of the infraction; 3) requiring that regulatory agencies put the fines that they impose and collect into the general treasury fund to be used toward retiring the national debt; and 4) requiring that enforcement actions comply with American due process concepts.
<p>Source: <i>Report of the 1995 White House Conference on Small Business</i>

<p>
