President, September 1993, p. 14.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="47">47</A></B></TT>     <U><i>Ibid</i></U>., p. 45.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="48">48</A></B></TT>     <U><i>Ibid</i>.</U>
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="49">49</A></B></TT>     Dallas L. Salisbury, 
<U><i>Government Mandating of Employee Benefits</i></U> (Washington,  D.C.: Employee
Benefits Research Institute, 1987).
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="50">50</A></B></TT>     The requirements of E.O. 12954
apply  to federal contracts of $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="51">51</A></B></TT>     Kenneth L. Deavers, &quot;The
Economic  Costs of Executive Order 12954: Barring Federal  Con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  tractors From Hiring Permanent
Striker Replacements,&quot; Employment Policy Foundation, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="52">52</A></B></TT>     <U><i>Chamber of Commerce v.  Reich</i></U>,
CA DC, No. 955242, 2/2/96.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="53">53</A></B></TT>     This is a reduction of just 0.4 
percent in discretionary spending from 1994 to 1999.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="54">54</A></B></TT>     White House press release, May
16, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="55">55</A></B></TT>     DoL has expanded credit card use
for  DoL purchases; some public paperwork burdens have been reduced;
dissemination time for the  Consumer Price Index has been reduced by 43 percent;
an OSHA field team reduced its  operations manual from 400 to 100 pages; DoL
GS13 to SES level employment is more  diversified; and reporting requirements
for labor  unions have been simplified to enhance compliance. U.S. Department of
Labor, 
<U><i>FY 1994 Accomplishments,</i></U> December 5, 1994.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="56">56</A></B></TT>     The National Performance Review, 
<U><i>Creating a Government That Works Better &amp;  Costs Less</i></U>, September 7,
1993.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="57">57</A></B></TT>    Scott A. Hodge and Adam Thierer,  &quot;The
National Performance Review: Falling Short  of Real Government Reform,&quot;
Heritage  Foundation <U><i>Backgrounder</i></U> No. 962, October 7, 1993.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="58">58 </A></B></TT>    Joseph A. Dear, Assistant
Secretary  for Occupational Safety and Health, U.S. Depart
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  ment of Labor, testimony before
the Committee on Labor and Human Resources, U.S.  Senate, November 29, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="59">59</A></B></TT>     Employers that provide this 
flexibility to their workers run the risk of  significant legal costs and
penalties should they be  investigated by the Department of Labor. For example,
Bill Pierce employed 25 salaried  professionals in his midwestern engineering
consulting business. Mr. Pierce also allowed  his workers to work flexible
schedules. During an investigation, the Department of Labor  declared that the
opportunity of flexible  schedules transformed Mr. Pierce's salaried workers 
into hourly employees subject to the FLSA's overtime provisions. DoL then
demanded that  Mr. Pierce pay his workers back overtime pay and penalties. The
result: Mr. Pierce had to  declare bankruptcy, and his employees lost their
jobs.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="60">60</A></B></TT>     Oklahoma Department of Labor, 
<U><i>Investigative Report: The Davis Bacon Act and  Fraudulent Wage Data
Submitted to the U.S. Department of  Labor</i></U>, July 11, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="61">61</A></B></TT>     Examples of welfare benefit plans
 are health insurance, apprenticeship plans, vacation plans, and severance
arrangements.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="62">62</A></B></TT>     Wilson, &quot;How to Close Down
the  Department of Labor.&quot;
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 --> 
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="63">63</A></B></TT>     The Department of Labor's goals
are  to &quot;foster, promote and develop the welfare  of wageearners, to
improve their working conditions, and to advance their opportunities  for
profitable employment.&quot;  Its original  focus was collecting information and
publishing reports on employment, wages, and working  conditions; reviewing the
effects of immigration  on the job market; and monitoring the use of child
labor.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="64">64</A></B></TT>     The Senate and House versions of
the  legislation (S. 143 and H.R. 1617) are significantly different and are
being reconciled in  a conference committee. A final version of the job training
legislation is expected to go  to the President for his signature this spring.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="65">65</A></B></TT>     Job placement assistance may
speed up  the transition from welfare to work and increase the number of hours
worked per year, but  that is entirely different from the primary  purpose of
training: betterpaying jobs.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="66">66</A></B></TT>     Mark Wilson, &quot;Welfare Reform
and Job  Training Programs: What Congress Doesn't Know Will Cost Taxpayers
Billions,&quot; Heritage  Foundation <U><i>F.Y.I</i></U>. No. 61, August 16, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="67">67</A></B></TT>     <U><i>From Red Tape to  Results</i></U>,
p. 45.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="68">68</A></B></TT>     Mark Wilson, &quot;Four Reasons
Why  Congress Should Repeal DavisBacon,&quot; Heritage  Founda
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  tion <U><i>Backgrounder</U> <U>Update</i></U>
No. 252, June 7, 1995.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="69">69</A></B></TT>     Oklahoma Department of Labor, 
<U><i>Investigative Report: The Davis Bacon Act and  Fraudulent Wage Data
Submitted to the U.S. Department of Labor.</i></U>
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="70">70</A></B></TT>     The SCA was amended in 1972 and
1976.  The purpose of these amendments was to expand  coverage, improve
administrative efficiency, and assure enforcement.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="71">71</A></B></TT>     Beverly Hall Burns, &quot;The
Service  Contract Act of 1965: Time to Revise or Repeal,&quot; 
<U><i>Villanova Law Review</i></U>, Vol. 29, No. 2 (19831984).
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="72">72</A></B></TT>     U.S. General Accounting Office, &quot;The
 Congress Should Consider Repeal of the Service Contract Act,&quot; 1983.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="73">73</A></B></TT>     In 1978, Congress recognized the 
benefit of these work arrangements and passed the  Federal Employees Flexible
and Compressed Work Schedules Act. This Act authorized a  threeyear experimental
period of alternative work  schedules for federal employees. The experiment  was
so successful that it was extended in 1982 and made permanent in 1985.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="74">74 </A></B></TT>    Charles W. Baird, &quot;Toward
Equality  and Justice in Labor Markets,&quot; <U><i>The Journal of  Social, Political and Economic Studies</U></i>, Vol.  20, No. 2 (Summer 1995).
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 --> 
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="75">75</A></B></TT>     The Commission on the Future  of
Worker-Management Relations was appointed by Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich
and  Secretary of Commerce Ronald H. Brown on March 24, 1993. Its mission was to
look at a broad  range of labormanagement issues and make recommendations.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="76">76</A></B></TT>     U.S. Department of Labor,
Commission  on the Future of Worker-Management Relations,
<U><i>Report and  Recommendations</i></U>, December 1994, p. xvii.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="77">77</A></B></TT>     <U><i>Communication Workers of
America v.  Beck</i></U>, 487 S. Ct. 735 (1988).
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="78">78</A></B></TT>     Deavers, &quot;The Economic Costs
of  Executive Order 12954: Barring Federal Contractors  From Hiring Permanent
Striker Replacements.&quot;
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="79">79</A></B></TT>     <U><i>Chamber of Commerce v.  Reich</i></U>,
CA DC, No. 955242, 2/2/96.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="80">80</A></B></TT>     Both the Senate and the House 
have passed job training legislation, but the Senate and House versions are
significantly  different. Those differences are being reconciled in a conference
committee, and a  final version of the job training legislation is expected to
go to the President for his  signature 
</P>
