<TITLE>
Chapter 8: Crime: Additional Information - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 8 - Additional Information</h3>
<center>
<b>Return to <A HREF="chpt8.html">Chapter 8</a> | <a href="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</a></b></center> 
<P>

&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Philadelphia, federal judge Norma Shapiro prevents judges from detaining many violent defendants before trial by prohibiting them from considering a defendant's prior criminal record, mental-health history, or drug dependency. The federal court also refuses to allow any pre-trial detention for such "non-violent" crimes as stalking, carjacking, robbery with a baseball bat, burglary, drug dealing, vehicular homicide, manslaughter, terrorist threats, and weapons violations. State and local judges in Philadelphia are prohibited from forcing defendants to appear at trial, and the city now has 50,000 fugitives from justice. Instead of being in jail, these individuals have gone on to commit numerous other crimes. Between 1994 and June 1995, Philadelphia police rearrested 9,732 of these criminals (previously released under federal court orders) for 79 murders, 959 robberies, 2,215 drug deals, 701 burglaries, 2,748 thefts, 90 rapes, 14 kidnapping charges, 1,113 assaults, 264 gun-law violations, and 127 drunk-driving incidents. 
<p>Source: John J. DiIulio, Jr., <i>How To Stop Federal Judges from Releasing Violent Criminals and Gutting Truth in Sentencing Laws,</i> Heritage Foundation Backgrounder No. 1020, February 22, 1995, p. 5
<p>
<center><B><A HREF="chpt7.html">Previous Chapter</A> | <A HREF="chpt9.html">Next Chapter</A> | <A HREF="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</A> | <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a> </B><p>
</center>
</BODY>
