<P><A NAME="14">14</A>     In what may be the oddest commentary  on the nature
of American elementary and secondary education, there is not a single  columnist
who writes a regular column about it for  the national media or news services.
Yet elementary and secondary education spends more  than $280 billion a year,
enrolls 44 million youngsters, and employs 3 million teachers (and  an equal
number of janitors, cooks, crossing guards, and so on). At the same time, the 
only nationally circulated magazines for and about education (other than union
magazines)  have tiny circulations. The best, <CITE><U>Education  Week</U></CITE>,
hovers around 60,000 subscribers a year.  The AFT's Shanker communicates with
the public  (and his members) through a paid advertisement  that runs in the
Sunday <CITE><U>New York Times </U></CITE>and 
<CITE><U>New 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  Republic</U></CITE>,<CITE><U>
</U></CITE>and the NEA's president, Keith  Geiger, now runs a similar ad in
<CITE><U>The Washington Post 
</U></CITE>and other print media. The antiintellectualism of the American 
public and the typical American educator is sobering.
</P>
