<P><TT><B><A NAME="1">1</A></B></TT> Charles Griffin was Deputy Director of The Heritage Foundation's Government Reform 
Project when he wrote this chapter. Since then, he 
has joined the staff of Representative David McIntosh. The views expressed in this chapter 
are Mr. Griffin's own.
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="2">2</A></B></TT> <i>U.S. Term Limits v. Thornton</i>, 115 S.Ct. 1842 (1995).
<P><TT><B><A NAME="3">3</A></B></TT> For further discussion, see &quot;The 
Reelection Machine,&quot; in Eric Felten, <i>The Ruling Class</i> (Washington, D.C.: Regnery Gateway, 1993), 
p. 183.
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="4">4</A></B></TT> Bundling is the practice of gathering checks from many individuals in an organization and delivering them as a package to a campaign in order to draw attention to the group. Soft money is a donation to a political party for use in general partybuilding efforts such as voter registration and get-out-the-vote campaigns.
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="5">5</A></B></TT> Federal Election Commission reports 
state that Fulani received $938,798.45 in public 
funds in 1988 and $2,013,323.42 in 1992.
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="6">6</A></B></TT> James T. Bennett and Thomas J. 
DiLorenzo, <i>Destroying Democracy: How Government Funds 
Partisan Politics</i> (Washington, D.C.: Cato 
Institute, 1985), p. 388.
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="7">7</A></B></TT> After the first $20 million in 
revenue, only 1 percent may be applied to advocacy activities. For example, an organization 
with nongrant revenues of $30 million would be limited to $1,100,000 in lobbying 
expenditures ($1,000,000 plus $100,000).
<P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="8">8</A></B></TT> A more complete discussion of the 
audit's results appears elsewhere in this chapter.
