<TITLE>
Chapter 13: Federal Race and Sex-based Preferences: Additional Information - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 13 - Additional Information</h3>
<center>
<b>Return to <A HREF="chpt13.html">Chapter 13</a> | <a href="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</a></b></center> 
<P>
<a href="#scrutiny">What is Strict Scrutiny</a><br>
<a href="#section">The Section 8(a) Program</a><br>
<a href="#how">How Race-Norming Works at Harvard's Department of Government</a><br>
<a href="#economic">The Economic Burden of Affirmative Action</a>
<p>
<a name="scrutiny">WHAT IS STRICT SCRUTINY?</a><p>
		There are two parts to the strict scrutiny standard:<ol>
<p><li>There must be a "compelling governmental interest" underlying an affirmative action measure; and 
<p><li>The measure must be "narrowly tailored" to serve that interest. </ol>
<p>	Courts typically look at six factors in deciding whether a race-conscious measure is narrowly tailored:<ol>
<p><li>Whether the government first considered race-neutral alternatives;
<p><li>Whether there is a waiver mechanism that limits the scope of the program to those who actually have been harmed by discrimination in the geographic region at issue;
<p><li>Whether race is the factor in determining eligibility for a program, or is just one of several factors in the decision-making process;
<p><li>The comparison of numerical targets with the number of qualified minorities in the relevant sector or industry; 
<p><li>Whether the program is subject to periodic review; and 
<p><li>Whether, and to what extent, the program imposes a burden on persons who do not belong to the favored groups and who are not personally responsible for the discrimination in question.
</ol>
<p>

<a name="section">THE SECTION 8(a) PROGRAM</a><p>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	One of the most controversial of the federal efforts to bestow an explicit advantage on favored racial and ethnic groups is the Small Business Administration's Section 8(a) program. The 8(a) program allows the SBA to channel federal procurement contracts to individuals and firms defined as socially and economically disadvantaged.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	Under the law, members of minority groups wishing to participate in this program are presumed to suffer from social and economic disadvantage. In contrast, non-minorities hoping to be classified as disadvantaged must prove social disadvantage "on the basis of clear and convincing evidence."
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Small Business Act defines socially disadvantaged individuals as "those who have been subjected to racial or ethnic prejudice or cultural bias because of their identity as a member of a group without regard to their individual qualities." Economically disadvantaged individuals are "those socially disadvantaged individuals whose ability to compete in the free enterprise system has been impaired due to diminished capital and credit opportunities as compared to others in the same business area who are not socially disadvantaged."
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	The Act establishes a government-wide goal for participation by these concerns at "not less than 5 percent of the total value of all prime contract and subcontract awards for each fiscal year" and requires the head of each federal agency to establish agency-specific goals for participation by these firms. In FY 1993, 5,414 companies participated in this program and received contracts valued at $4.5 billion.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	For a business owner to qualify for the Small Business Administration's disadvantaged business program, his net worth may not exceed $250,000. But in arriving at this calculation, the SBA does not include either the owner's equity in his companies and homes or the wealth of his spouse. In 1994, federal auditors selected five SBA district offices and examined 50 supposedly disadvantaged companies that had received at least $10 million each in federal contracts. Among their findings:<ul>
<p><li>35 of the 50 owners were worth more than $1 million each; 
<p><li>Five owners received salaries and bonuses totaling between $1 million and $2.5 million over a two-year period. Seven others earned more than $750,000; 
<p><li>Over a dozen reported equity stakes in their firms of between $1 million and $9 million; 
<p><li>Five had homes worth $800,000 to $1.4 million.</ul><p>
Angie Cannon, "Soaked by Small Biz: Feds Aid Minority Millionaires," <I>New York Daily News,</I> June 11, 1995, p. 26.<p>



<a name="how">HOW RACE-NORMING WORKS AT HARVARD'S DEPARTMENT OF GOVERNMENT</a>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	Applications from "underrepresented minorities" receive a bright green sticker and a pink status sheet, which are removed so the application can be read blind. A panel of professors narrows the 600-700 applications down to about 45. Then the stickers are reattached, and department officials review the applications to ascertain how many minorities were accepted. At this point, Harvard accepts any minority applicant who "would complete the program if admitted."
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	If this standard were applied to all applicants, the department would admit 200 to 300 students a year. Instead, it admits from 35 to 45. 
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	The numbers: 570 students applied to the government department in the fall of 1995. Of the 35 minority applicants, six (17 percent) were accepted. In contrast, only 27 of the 535 non-minority applicants (about 5 percent) were accepted.

<p>

<a name="economic">THE ECONOMIC BURDEN OF AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</a><p>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	Some economists have estimated the costs that affirmative action policies impose on the economy and on individual businesses:
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	<b>A 6.5 Percent Mandate.</b>  Economist Peter Griffin estimates that the cost of complying with affirmative action rules and regulations for firms that do business with the federal government amounted to 6.5 percent of all costs in 1980.*
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<b>A 4 Percent Burden on Gross Domestic Product.</b>  John Hunter, Professor of Psychology at Michigan State University, estimates that total U.S. output would be about 2.5 percent, or $150 billion, higher if every employer in the country subject to federal law were free to use employment tests and select on merit.** In addition, Peter Brimelow and Leslie Spencer estimate that the administrative costs associated with affirmative action since 1980 amount to approximately $113 billion per year, or another 1.5 percent of GDP. Thus, the total negative impact on GDP is estimated to be about 4 percent per year.***
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	<b>The Cost to California Taxpayers.</b> In a November 24, 1993, letter to State Attorney General Dan Lungren, the California Joint Legislative Budget Committee noted that the state government spends roughly $200 million per year on affirmative action and other race-based programs. 
<p>* See Peter Griffin, "The Impact of Affirmative Action on Labor Demand: A Test of Some Implications of the Le Chatelier Principle," <I>The Review of Economics and Statistics,</I> May 1992, p. 259.<br> ** See John A. Hartigan and Alexandra K. Wigdor, eds., <I>Fairness in Employment Testing: Validity Generalization, Minority Issues, and the General Aptitude Test Battery</I> (Washington, D.C., National Academy Press, 1989).<br> *** See Brimelow and Spencer, "When Quotas Replace Merit, Everybody Suffers," p. 99.

<p>
<center><B><A HREF="chpt12.html">Previous Chapter</A> | <A HREF="chpt14.html">Next Chapter</A> | <A HREF="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</A> | <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a> </B><p>
</center>
</BODY>
