<html>
<title>Government Relations -- Heritage Departments</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><IMG SRC="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a></center>

<h2>Government Relations</h2>
<hr>
<p>
Led by Vice President Michael Franc, the twelve-member staff of The Heritage Foundation's Government Relations Department serves as an institutional link between the Heritage research team and the policymaking community, providing Congress and the Executive Branch with timely information and policy recommendations on matters of current interest.  House Liaison <a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a> and Senate Liaison <a href="/heritage/staff/carter.html">Mary Anne Carter</a> meet daily with Congressional staff to educate them on research findings.
<p>
The staff prides itself on being on top of the hot issues, in contact with key Members and staff, and in delivering important policy information in a timely, easy-to-use manner.  Additionally, Mason and staff are regularly contacted by the media to discuss Heritage analysis of current issues.
<p>
Since 1992, the Candidate Education Project has made our analysts and research  available to Democratic and Republican congressional and presidential campaigns. The first year the Department received calls from over 130 campaigns. The number rose to over 235 campaigns in 1994. For the 1996 election cycle, we have already received calls or visits from 30 campaigns. The grand finale of the Candidate Education Project is the New Members' Orientation Conference. All freshmen Members, their spouses and Chiefs of Staff are invited to this three-day issues seminar in early December, following the elections. The 1994 Conference hosted 60 Members and forced the cancellation of the traditional freshman orientation conference at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. 
<P>
Directed by <a href="/heritage/staff/weinstein.html">Kenneth R. Weinstein</a>, the Government Reform Project includes Union Watch, the Government Integrity Project, and the Congress Project.  Union Watch examines the political activities of labor unions.  Although organized labor's political efforts are generally funded through compulsory union dues, public opinion surveys regularly indicate that the agenda promoted by labor leaders is often at odds with the views held by the union rank and file.  The <a href="/heritage/library/index/h3.html">Government Integrity Project</a> seeks to highlight the practice of permitting tax- exempt organizations which engage in political or legislative advocacy to receive funds from the federal government. Weinstein also directs Heritage's effort to reform Congress, enact term limits and promote campaign finance reform.  Former Congress Project Director Dave Mason oversaw the publication of the book <a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/ruli.html">"The Ruling Class: Inside the Imperial Congress"</a>.
















<p>
Under the direction of Karen Miller, Heritage participates in the  <a href="/heritage/
jobs/jobs.html">Conservative Placement Network</a>. Since its inception in 1991, 
Heritage has helped place hundreds of conservatives in public policy positions.
<p>
In conjunction with Heritage's Research Department, the Government Relations staff has contributed to many publications, such as <a href="/heritage/issues96/tblcon.html"><i>Issues `96</i></a>, <a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/issu.html"><i>Issues '94: The Candidate's Briefing Book</i></a>, <i>The 
New Member's Guide To The Issues</i>, <a 
href="/townhall/townhall_shop/roll.html"><i>Rolling Back Government: A Budget Plan 
to Rebuild America</i></a>, and <i>Freeing America's Farmers: The Heritage Plan for 
Rural Prosperity</i>. These timely publications are distributed to targeted congressional 
lists and congressional briefings are arranged.
<p>
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
</body>
